        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "Living with dyslexia by Sarah Bennett\n§ 1. I had just started primary school and our class was given a reading test. I was taken to a small quiet room where a kind-looking woman placed a page in front of me with rows of short words. 'Please read the first line for me,' she said gently. I didn't know why she was smiling, because the letters on the page kept slipping about like tiny black insects. I managed the first two words, but she asked me to continue and I simply could not. She handed me another sheet that seemed identical to the first. I grew upset. 'The letters keep moving,' I said. That was how I learned that I had dyslexia, a common learning difficulty that affects the way the brain processes written language. Most of the other children in the room had seen ordinary rows of short English words; I saw a jumble of shapes that refused to stay in place.\n§ 2. I am far from alone. It is estimated that roughly one in ten people in the UK has some form of dyslexia. Researchers say it is largely down to genetics, and there is increasing talk of early intervention programmes that can retrain the brain, though I cannot say I feel especially drawn to any kind of brain-training therapy. Personally, I do not feel like I 'suffer' from dyslexia at all.\n§ 3. In general, people with dyslexia simply adjust to the printed world around them. For example, when I read a bus timetable, the key thing for me is not the numbers but their position on the page. Of course, with all the graffiti on the bus stops in my neighbourhood, I am just glad when the timetables are still readable at all.\n§ 4. Unfortunately, not everything is so easy to work around. When my printer is low on ink, a small text message flashes up on the screen in thin grey letters. That would be fine, except that the words blur together and I can rarely read the warning in time. A much better system would be the one on my coffee machine: instead of showing a written message, it blinks an orange dot until you refill the water tank.\n§ 5. Life is full of small frustrations like that. Because letters sometimes jump for me, I do occasionally send a text message with a very odd-looking word in the middle of it.\n§ 6. However, there are bigger problems that can occur when professionals do not take dyslexia into account. I once nearly failed a school exam because a long reading question was printed in a very narrow, italic font. To me all of the letters looked almost the same. Similar problems still crop up in textbooks and examinations today.\n§ 7. Moments like those aside, in my own life dyslexia has been more of an inconvenience than a serious problem. People like me live just like anyone else. We can continue to do so as long as people in positions of responsibility take steps to prevent any problems before they occur.",
