        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "§ 1. Sometimes the road to survival is long. 'Old Benjamin', a giant Aldabra tortoise, is one of only a handful of his particular population left in the wild and thus profoundly isolated. Living far out in the Indian Ocean on a remote atoll in the Seychelles, he is officially among the rarest reptiles on Earth.\n§ 2. No creature better captures the natural history of the Seychelles than the giant Aldabra tortoise. There used to be hundreds of thousands of them wandering the islands of the region. Observations of these tortoises by early naturalists even contributed to modern theories about island evolution.\n§ 3. Sadly, however, mostly because for centuries passing whalers had been capturing the giant tortoises for fresh meat, there are now only an estimated hundred thousand left in the wild. Of the several known island populations, most are already thought to be extinct, as was the Aldabra tortoise of the smaller atolls until Old Benjamin was found in 1985. This came as a pleasant surprise to scientists since no other tortoises of his specific lineage had been recorded in the area since the 1920s.\n§ 4. Since Benjamin was discovered, he has become the star attraction at the Seychelles Tortoise Sanctuary where conservationists have been hoping to preserve some of his genes by mating him with another tortoise. Two females from the main Aldabra atoll, the most closely related to Benjamin's line that could be tracked down, were placed into his enclosure with him in 2002, but he failed to take the hint.\n§ 5. Then, Professor Linda Morris, an evolutionary biologist from Oxford University, came up with a possible reason why Old Benjamin was not finding true romance with the ladies from the main atoll. Perhaps, she suggested, they were simply too different from him to be a suitable match. Sailors frequently carried the tortoises from one island to another, she pointed out. So there could be a perfect match for Benjamin alive and well on the main atoll or even on a more distant island.\n§ 6. To begin testing her theory, Professor Morris compared DNA from nine tortoises of Benjamin's lineage with blood samples from thirty-two giant tortoises living on the main Aldabra atoll. Among these samples, they found one tortoise showing clear signs of shared ancestry (происхождение). Sadly, however, the newly discovered tortoise was not suitable for Benjamin: it was also male.\n§ 7. Morris with her team intends to return to the main atoll and take blood from more than three thousand tortoises. If they do indeed find a female of the right lineage, they hope to bring her to Benjamin's enclosure and attempt to breed the pair. The possibility remains, then, that Old Benjamin may one day not be so alone after all.",
