        "text": "An interview with a couple who own a holiday cottage in the Scottish Highlands\nWhy did you decide to buy a holiday home here?\nWe have always enjoyed travelling and spending weekends in different parts of the country. It made sense to us to have somewhere of our own that we could return to as often as we liked. (A43) ___ It has everything we were looking for: mountains, lochs, peaceful countryside for walking and a charming village just down the road. We looked at some very isolated locations but in the end decided we wanted to be close to a community. We love being able to stroll down to the shop in the morning for fresh milk and take a short walk to the pub for supper. It was also important to us that the property would be easy to reach for short breaks, so the fact that there is a small regional airport an hour away was a key factor. (A44) ___ We love both of our houses even though they are completely different in character and in very different landscapes.\nHow did you find this particular property?\nWe did a lot of research into the area we liked and we studied many online listings. Then we went to an agency which specialised in Highland properties. They were extremely helpful and over four days they showed us a number of different cottages as well as a few empty plots of land with planning permission for a new build. (A45) ___ We spent ages chatting with the owners who were selling and wandering round the garden as well as the cottage. It's not a large house; there are only two bedrooms, but it is exactly what we wanted. It has a wonderful stone patio with views over the loch. It is truly picturesque. In fact it is a beautiful spot to stay at any time of the year.\nWhat do you like most about owning a second home?\n(A46) ___ We spend many holidays here ourselves and sometimes friends and family join us, but we also let friends and family borrow it whenever they want. It means the cottage is lived in more, and the more it is used the better. We also love that we have made some good friends here. (A47) ___ It means we never feel like strangers when we arrive. Another thing we appreciate is that there is always somewhere new to explore in the Highlands as well as favourite spots to return to.\nWould you like to move and live here permanently?\nNo. There is too much we would miss back in the south: good friends and close family. (A48) ___ We might come up for a month or more at a time instead of a week or two as we do now. But we bought the cottage as a holiday home, not as somewhere to live all year round. We love having both of our homes and don't want to give up either of them.",
