        "block": "text-completion",
        "blockLabel": "Text Completion",
        "text": "On my first trip to Vietnam I had an unexpectedly chaotic experience. I had arrived in Hanoi very early in the morning after a long, delayed flight from Paris. My plan was to go straight to an old town called Hoi An that a colleague had recommended. By the time I finally reached the little train station in Hoi An, I had been travelling for more than twenty-six hours.\n\nAs soon as I stepped off the overnight train, I was immediately surrounded by local hosts offering me rooms in their family homes. I chose a friendly woman called Linh, and she led me through narrow lanes to her small guesthouse, where she showed me to a pretty room with its own tiny bathroom and a view of a lemon tree. (A43) ___ After getting dressed, I went down to the courtyard.\n\nThere, Linh was sitting with a young woman called Mai, who spoke Vietnamese and English fluently. While we drank green tea, Mai translated politely for us. It turned out that Linh's daughter Hương was studying medicine abroad, so Mai was staying in her room for the summer. Linh had suggested that Mai should show me around the old town. (A44) ___ We finished our tea, said goodbye to Linh and headed out through the wooden front gate.\n\nAs we walked slowly in the direction of the ancient riverside, Mai pointed out various landmarks I should remember: a house with a bright red door and a potted frangipani, a small yellow pagoda with a little bench outside, a noodle stall on a corner where there was always a friendly tabby cat. (A45) ___ I wondered briefly if I should go straight back to the guesthouse and have an early night, but I decided I would be better off having a proper bowl of phở first before retracing my steps.\n\nBy the time Mai and I reached the old Japanese bridge, it was already time for her to head to her evening shift. (A46) ___ Even though I was very hungry, I decided I should make sure I could find my way back to Linh's guesthouse while there was still some daylight left.\n\nFrom the bridge, I set off down a narrow lane I could have sworn was the very same one Mai and I had followed earlier that afternoon. There was a noodle stall on a corner but the tabby cat was nowhere in sight, and there were several houses with bright red doors and frangipani trees in pots. I had no idea at all where I actually was. (A47) ___ I began to wonder if Linh and her guesthouse were just an elaborate dream I had invented out of sheer exhaustion.\n\nEventually, in a moment of real panic, I stopped a kind-looking old man who was watering his plants on a doorstep. Surely he would know where Linh lived. (A48) ___ And indeed, after a long, patient conversation in a mixture of broken English and my three words of Vietnamese, he took me straight back to Linh's wooden gate, where she was already waiting for me with a worried smile.",
