        "block": "text-completion",
        "blockLabel": "Text Completion",
        "text": "The stress and strong emotions people experience when they start studying in a new country, such as far from home, are known as study-abroad culture shock. (A43) ___ They develop from the difficulties faced when students have to adapt to a new academic system and don't fully understand how to operate within it.\n Helena Novak, who is Czech, spent three years at a university in Spain. 'Everything felt exciting at the beginning,' says Helena. 'I was delighted by the warm weather and the friendly people, but as I settled into my new routine, I began to feel overwhelmed and anxious. Trying to rent a room, register with the local administration in a small town and obtain my student card seemed impossible. (A44) ___ I could not grasp the Spanish way of doing things. There were moments when I wanted to pack my bags and go straight back to Prague. Eventually, though, I got a hold of my new environment and felt at home.'\n Psychologist Daniel Harper explains what Helena describes as the distinct phases of culture shock. 'The majority of people who move to a new country go through the following phases. The first, known as the honeymoon phase, lasts for a few weeks and is characterised by viewing the new culture as something wonderful. (A45) ___ However, after some time, the new culture starts to create feelings of frustration. People may begin to miss their old country and the way of life there. (A46) ___ After about six months, most of them enter the adjustment phase, which is when they get used to their new culture. They learn how to behave appropriately and have accepted the new culture.'\n Yet not all people react in the same way, as Daniel explains. 'There are three different forms of adjustment. Many people actually find it impossible to accept the new culture. (A47) ___ Others integrate so fully into their new environment that they lose their original identity. Finally, there are those people who successfully manage to combine the best parts of their new culture with their old culture. These people experience few problems and are the happiest of all.'\n Daniel has this advice for people thinking of studying abroad. 'Before you travel, learn as much as you can about the new country so that you are better prepared for what you will face. Obviously, learning the local language will help. (A48) ___ You can share your feelings with fellow international students who will provide a support network for you and are a very valuable resource because they've already been in your shoes. Keep an open mind about the new culture and enjoy the differences rather than see them as obstacles.'",
