        "block": "text-completion",
        "blockLabel": "Text Completion",
        "text": "Anna Fischer makes indie podcasts about the lives of young people in small towns. She records with a basic microphone and asks her guests to speak from their own kitchens. Her low-budget episodes are hardly ever promoted by big platforms. By distributing digitally, Ms Fischer is making a living.\n Technology was expected to help independent creators like her. A few years ago it was predicted that the Internet would massively increase the supply of small niche shows and widen their audiences. That has certainly happened. (A43) ___ Mega-hits are also tightening their grip on audiences, whether it's in the area of podcasts, music, television or books. The growth of both small niche products and huge sell-out successes has been at the expense of the things in the middle which are just moderately popular — the near misses.\n (A44) ___ As in the past, people still want to have something to talk about with their friends. Which is why the latest bestselling podcast still breaks new download records. Research shows that listeners still choose mega-hits more often than less well-known shows and books.\n Furthermore, all the technology that has made niche content so much more accessible has also proved handy for pushing mega-hits. Missed the last popular episode? (A45) ___\n Mega-hits are doing well not in spite of the fact that people have more choice in entertainment, but because of it. Imagine walking into a music shop which has more than 50 million songs, as Spotify does, all of them arranged alphabetically. Making up your mind would be impossible! (A46) ___\n Is this increasingly more common separation into mega-hits and niches good or bad? It certainly makes life harder for media companies. In a world where entertainment choices are growing, it is more important than ever to make a big impact with your product. (A47) ___ The possibility of failing can make people anxious and more conservative. Podcast series must be successful quickly or they will be dropped by sponsors.\n These days, with so many options, there is rarely nothing good to listen to. So the media industry must raise its game. Intelligent people naturally wish that more money were available to produce the kind of music, podcasts and television programmes they like. (A48) ___ Some may love listening to a show about the history of ballet; others may want to spend an hour being told how to keep pet parrots. But not many want to do either of these things, which explains why such shows are niche products. There are only a few things that can be guaranteed to delight large numbers of people. They are known as mega-hits.",
