        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "For Olympic gold medallist Sarah Collins losing the London Marathon was the biggest disappointment of her career.\n§ 1. The London Marathon is a unique event. It pulls on the primal instincts of human endurance and the desire to push limits. Everyone picks a favourite. The millions who watch worldwide on TV will cheer on either the British runners or the visiting Kenyans and Ethiopians.\n§ 2. From an early age I shouted for the British team. I could never understand why the runners at the back didn't simply run faster. It all looked so terribly obvious and easy. Like a coach in the making, my nine-year-old self would tell the slower athletes: 'You're losing! Run faster.' Little did I know that a decade later I'd be racing through the same streets, stuck in that miserable second place.\n§ 3. The hardest test I faced as an elite runner presented itself at 4.45 a.m. every day. The alarm always tested my resolution. It presented a choice between continuing my quest to win the Marathon, or sleep. I came painfully close to throwing away my dreams on quite a few occasions. Instead, I would drag my aching body out from under the covers into the morning darkness. A typical day started with a long run around the park. A quick breakfast preceded the afternoon session at the track and then it was back home for massage and recovery.\n§ 4. A Marathon campaign means nine months of dedication. Avoiding injury, I somehow managed to reach the start line in excellent form. My only objective was to beat a heavily favoured Kenyan runner. Two days before the race, our team's best pacemaker was forced to withdraw on medical grounds. It was a brutal setback for our inexperienced support team.\n§ 5. Eventually, the time had come and we stepped onto the start line with the cries of the crowd around us. The starter (стартёр) raised his pistol. Attention. Go! My trainers pounded through heavy rain and into a cold, unrelenting headwind. The weather conditions were bleak, but less bleak than those arriving in the minds of my rivals. I refused to accept the inevitable, but it was clear to the millions of people watching that I had already lost the battle. Then the Kenyan runner suddenly kicked again somewhere past the twentieth mile and at that point it really was all over. My memories of the final stretch are hazy, but I'm sure there was a definite point at which my legs failed. Despite asking for more, there was nothing left to give. The finish line brought total exhaustion.\n§ 6. What appeals to me is the simple and brutal nature of the event. Runner against runner. Them or us. That is what drew me to the event. The athletes must commit fully in search of the win. This is why it matters. That is why the losing runner will hurt so much: there's no preparation for losing.",
