        "text": "§ 1. The Greenmoor Science Fair is one of the longest-running school science events in Scotland. Founded in 1982, Greenmoor is a week-long gathering for young inventors under the age of sixteen. There are pupils of every age group, and they bring projects covering every scientific field you can imagine. It really is something to see the sparkle in the children's eyes as they unload their equipment from their parents' cars and drag big cardboard boxes into the school hall.\n§ 2. Organisers of the fair know that a whole week of demonstrations, debates and judging can be exhausting for young participants. For this reason, they have built into the schedule a full afternoon in which none of the standards of behaviour normally required at the fair apply. Children can rest in the garden, play football, read or simply chat. Several of the teachers we spoke to said this was the single most important change they had introduced in the last ten years.\n§ 3. Among this year's participants is fourteen-year-old Blanca from Seville, who is presenting a model wind turbine made from recycled plastic. Before the event, Blanca admitted that she hadn't been sure whether to attend at all. She had only started her project three months earlier and worried that her English wasn't good enough for the interviews. In the end, her teacher persuaded her that the opportunity to meet other student scientists was too valuable to miss.\n§ 4. Luigi, aged fifteen, has travelled from Naples with a small robot that picks up plastic bottles from beaches. He told us that his main ambition at Greenmoor is not to win a prize, but rather to make a positive first impression on the visiting professors from the University of Edinburgh, who have been known to offer laboratory internships to promising young inventors.\n§ 5. The judges take their work very seriously. They award points for originality, scientific method, clarity of explanation and the environmental usefulness of each project. Every participant receives detailed written comments at the end of the week.\n§ 6. For the Greenmoor organisers the most rewarding moment comes on the final evening, when children explain how much they have benefited from the experience — new friendships, new ideas and, for some, the confidence to continue working on their projects long after the fair is over.",
