        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "§ 1. It's hard to believe that electric scooters have only been a common sight in European cities for a few years. They're now so familiar that it's surprising when a city centre doesn't have dozens of them parked on every corner. As I walk to the office in the mornings, all I see are commuters zipping past on silent two-wheelers, eyes fixed firmly on the road. When I step off the pavement at a zebra crossing, I have to look in six directions rather than two, because every rider is concentrating hard on their handlebars and their smartphone rather than on the pedestrians around them.\n§ 2. A hundred years ago, urban transport changed significantly when the electric tram was introduced to most European capitals. Trams had much simpler features than the scooters of today — you couldn't steer them, you couldn't park them, and they certainly didn't come with an app. Still, they gave ordinary workers the chance to live far from the factory, which transformed city life and let us communicate with people who were far away by bringing distant neighbourhoods within daily reach.\n§ 3. The thing most people worry about today is not the technology itself but what happens when you mix it with work. Many employees now have company apps installed directly on their own scooters, so a delayed delivery can be followed in real time by a manager sitting at home. In the writer's view, such tools make it difficult to stop working, because the boundary between office and street has been erased.\n§ 4. Tourism is another area where scooters are changing the way we travel. In coastal towns, visitors can rent a vehicle directly from their hotel and ride along the seafront at sunset, snapping photos at every stop. Locals, however, complain that the profiles of these tourists — where they come from, what they post online, which streets they film most often — are shared more widely than most riders would expect.\n§ 5. Perhaps the clearest sign of our dependence on electric scooters came last winter when a small earthquake struck a city in southern Italy. Within minutes, hundreds of riders had uploaded shaky videos, some of which turned out to show different streets or different dates altogether. The writer mentions this earthquake mainly to show that some news might not be accurate, especially when it is filmed from a moving scooter.",
