        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "§ 1. Many people know from an early age what they are destined to do. But for Nina Carver it was a chance visit to a pottery studio which led her to take up the profession. 'I went to an open day at the studio of the famous ceramicist Luka Alvarez. A friend persuaded me to go with her, but I wasn't particularly interested in any craft subjects at all. As I watched him throw a huge bowl, I felt something like an electric shock,' she says. 'Within a week I'd gone out and bought my first wheel.'\n§ 2. However, mastering the craft wasn't as easy as Nina had imagined, and it was some time before she was happy with the work she was producing. 'Of course, my first efforts were absolutely dreadful. One of the things that I've learned is that rather than just sitting at the wheel when the feeling takes you, you've got to treat it as a profession, so every day I set aside a few hours for practice.'\n§ 3. Desert landscapes were an obvious place to start for Nina. She had been brought up in a number of arid regions in the American South-West. 'There was a stretch of red sandstone canyon very near where I used to play, and I remember feeling excited and a little scared at the same time. I was always imagining what might be hidden behind the rocks. Perhaps that's why I'm drawn to shapes that look harsh and dramatic!' This early experience has led to her specialising in sculptural vessels inspired by rock formations. Since she was living near a large art market when she started making pieces, it was easy for her to show her work regularly and get to know collectors. Then a friend suggested that she should ask a downtown gallery to sell her work. Nina didn't expect anyone to be interested, but the response was so strong that she was able to give up her teaching job and become a full-time ceramicist.\n§ 4. She admits that she had been making vessels inspired by photos of the Grand Canyon for several years before she finally saw it with her own eyes. 'When I finally made it to Arizona, just being there affected my work dramatically. I felt a strong pull towards the colours and the layered textures, and this has influenced my pieces ever since.'\n§ 5. And what advice would Nina give to young ceramicists? 'The main problem with trying to develop a genuine style is that inspiration rarely shows up on demand. You should, therefore, be prepared to wait quite a while before you find the subject that really moves you. Knowing what it is that you're aiming for will definitely help you, rather than just throwing pot after pot at random. Of course, sometimes you strike lucky and get that one-off perfect piece, but usually it's just down to a matter of patience.'",
