        "text": "§ 1. To raise awareness of sustainable travel, a magazine and a radio station challenged sisters Emma and Clara Wilson, well-known rally drivers, to take part in an unusual race that would pit old technology against new, and sister against sister. Across the rolling green hills of the Scottish Borders, Emma and Clara would race to the same finish line, Emma driving a classic petrol sports car on winding roads, Clara driving a brand new electric vehicle along the same route.\n§ 2. 'I can hardly wait,' Emma said, as the sisters lined up at the starting point. 'I've never tried anything quite like this before: it's thrilling! These roads offer incredible views — and the engine noise adds to the fun.' Clara was equally eager — though in contrast to Emma's leather driving jacket, she was wearing an ordinary fleece. Not that the cold was troubling her confidence. 'Honestly,' she said, 'I've watched her drive on ice before, so I'm not even sure she'll reach the finish in one piece.'\n§ 3. The race set off from the beautiful shores of St Mary's Loch and was to finish at the highest pass in the region, Devil's Beef Tub. Barely time for a quick hug and they were away. The next time the sisters would meet would be at the finishing post.\n§ 4. Emma's early confidence took an immediate blow. Barely twenty seconds into the drive and she faced her first obstacle. Emerging heavily from a farm gate and onto the road was an enormous tractor carrying hay. 'If Clara beats me, it's all down to this farmer!' A few moments later, once the tractor had pulled over, Emma was back in control.\n§ 5. Clara, meanwhile, was struggling with a steep gradient. The battery was draining much faster than expected, forcing her to turn off the heating and slow right down, a chance to demonstrate her patience and skill behind the wheel.\n§ 6. In the petrol car, her sister encountered another local obstacle. The Border villages and the single-track roads that connect them were never designed for speed. Emma attempted to negotiate a ridiculously tight humpback bridge. The car slowed to a crawl as she inched forward between the stone walls, hoping no one was coming the other way. With barely an inch to spare on either side, she eased the car through.\n§ 7. At the finish line, after nearly two hours, the sisters compared their experiences. The electric car had arrived first, with energy to spare, surprising everyone present. Emma laughed and admitted defeat, conceding that the future of motoring might well be quieter than she had imagined.",
