        "text": "§ 1. In 2012, Rosa Ventura became the first woman to dive solo to the deepest part of the Mariana Trench. That meant plunging through crushing pressure, battling freezing temperatures and risking catastrophic equipment failure. Just six months later, she completed a similar dive in the Puerto Rico Trench. Now she is back on a research vessel, preparing for an expedition she says is somewhat of a different kind. This time there is far more at stake. Rosa and two colleagues will set out on a three-month, 5,000-kilometre expedition along the Pacific Ring of Fire, taking detailed measurements of plastic pollution levels on the deep seabed. Nobody has ever done this before, and she knows the results will be of vital importance to the scientific community. This will be the truest picture yet of what human waste is doing to the ecosystems that cover the deepest regions of our oceans.\n§ 2. Rosa and her husband live in a coastal village with their two children. 'They were two and six when I last went, and I made a mistake in the way I said goodbye. I thought it would be a good idea to say to my daughter, \"You're in charge now, look after your dad and your brother.\" She absolutely took it to heart, asking her dad how he was all the time, but the strain eventually became too much. While it was well intentioned, it was an unfair thing to do.' For similar reasons she is planning to have very little contact with them while at sea. 'If you call them, you remind them how far away you are.'\n§ 3. She is spending these last days before departure preparing her kit. 'Out at sea, one is practically unable to fix anything,' she says. With her will be Carlos Peña, one of the world's leading marine biologists, and the expedition photographer, Yuki Tanaka. They will be supported by a crew of eight, flying in spare parts by helicopter. Being part of a team is actually more stressful to someone with her mentality, says Rosa, and something else is on her mind too. 'I'm going to be 52 on Friday. I've done far less training than I'm comfortable with.' Why? 'Organisational pressures have taken up most of my time this year.'\n§ 4. When she compares this mission with her earlier solo dives, Rosa recognises how different it feels. 'Back then, only scientists cared about what I was doing. This time, fishermen, environmentalists, and even governments are following our progress closely. That makes me feel proud, of course, because it means the value of this work is finally being recognised far beyond the laboratory. Many more people will gain something from the measurements we bring back — and that is genuinely worth the risk.'",
