        "text": "§ 1. He is not much taller than his violin and struggles to reach the upper strings, but that has not reduced the amount of excitement about Diego Rossi, a six-year-old violinist from Argentina. He even has his own website, and there cannot be many boys his age who have an official biography that stretches to more than 1,200 words. At an age when most boys just want to play with their friends and may not even have started primary school, Diego is already famous. But his plan now seems to be to concentrate on music, and to cut down on the endless media appearances.\n§ 2. An offer from a special music conservatory in Austria has meant Diego's entire family have now relocated there to support him. His father is a confident man. 'If I'm going to make a prediction, I'd say he could become one of the greatest violinists of his generation,' he has said. Critics have responded that he is either crazy or deliberately exaggerating his son's prospects. 'I suppose if I were in their shoes, I'd have made a snap judgement too, but I get really annoyed when people don't have the full facts. It would also be nice if they actually bothered to come to a rehearsal and hear what he is capable of.'\n§ 3. Leading conductor Elsa Hartmann has listened to Diego and, although she is impressed, adds a note of caution. 'I think it's notoriously tricky to make accurate predictions about a child's future at this stage. There are some children who don't develop either the stamina or the emotional depth until they are 16 or so, and it is only then that you can make a realistic decision about whether they should pursue a full professional career. Diego looks as if he is having fun playing on stage, and there's no evidence he's being pushed to do this against his will, but we don't know how he's going to develop either technically or artistically.'\n§ 4. Ex-prodigy Andrea Volkov, who left performing before she was 20, says, 'He's obviously incredibly dedicated. I was not dissimilar in that respect. But more impressive is the fact that Diego goes through all the endless scales with a big smile on his face. He always seems ready for more, whereas I can remember feeling miserable because of all the pressure. I was painfully aware of not having much freedom. Sometimes I just wanted to put my violin away and forget music for a while.' Diego's father insists that he won't be disappointed if Diego eventually decides music isn't for him. 'I just want him to stay healthy and to enjoy his life. Our love is not tied to applause and reviews. We are just doing our best to make sure that he stays grounded and down to earth.'",
