        "text": "Jazz the Night\nMusic journalist Emma Carter meets young actors from this popular jazz show.\n\n§ 1. Jazz the Night, a theatrical show where actors also have to be excellent saxophonists and pianists, opened in Paris last year, after four years in Canada, where it was voted 'Best Musical' three times! But doing the show with an all-French cast of actors was challenging. France puts more limits on how many performances young actors can do weekly — in Canada, they're allowed to do more shows. Because of this, twice as many actors were required here. Luckily, the director found plenty of talented Paris-based actors, and they've just won their first 'Best Musical' award. Although the theatre in Paris is bigger than the Canadian venue, it's been full every night, with everyone wanting to hear the songs that first became popular in North America.\n§ 2. I met 12-year-old Lucas, one of the show's actors. 'It's brilliant that I get paid to play,' he said, 'especially a beautiful and expensive Yamaha saxophone.' He told me how busy the young actors are. 'We have normal school lessons each day at the theatre. While the teacher's great, I miss my old school mates.' And what do they think of the show? 'Well, my whole class came! The theatre does special deals on tickets for schools. They absolutely loved it and that made me feel really confident. My parents come when they can, but it's expensive for them,' he explained.\n§ 3. When I said I also play saxophone, Lucas found a spare one and invited me to play along with him and the other young actors. We played Blue Rain, a song I hadn't heard before. Lucas took me through it and I was very pleased with myself when I finally got it right. I was impressed by Lucas's ability and wished I had similar skills. I was just trying to keep up and was glad the show's director wasn't there to hear my mistakes!\n§ 4. While the young actors were already musicians, with some playing several instruments, none had played in a jazz band before. Fortunately, they've found it easy to blend their sounds with the adult band members. What they do find difficult, however, is looking relaxed while playing complicated jazz solos in front of a full theatre. 'It feels strange to smile and breathe naturally when your fingers are moving so fast,' Lucas admits. 'But our coach tells us that the audience can always tell when we're tense — so we're working on it.'",
