        "text": "Diego Ramirez talks about attending a food festival.\n\n§ 1. I've always been passionate about food, whether it's something I'm cooking at home, sampling at a street market or enjoying at a restaurant. But my greatest love has always been going to food festivals. They are a great place to taste dishes from your favourite cuisines and to enjoy yourself with friends, and they are also an opportunity to meet new people. But the experience can be spoilt if you don't take care, so here are some things I've learnt along the way.\n§ 2. Let's start with what you should take. You can't be sure of the weather so I'd suggest preparing for anything. Take sun cream. If it's sunny you'll be out in the open all day. And don't forget something to keep you dry in a sudden shower, even if it's only a large plastic rubbish bag. Your mobile phone and charger are essentials, of course, but apart from these don't take anything you wouldn't want to lose. Take comfortable shoes as you'll be on your feet all day, and bring a small rucksack for the food you want to carry away.\n§ 3. Once you're there, take a tour of the area so you know exactly where everything is. If you're with friends, agree on meeting points. Some food stalls are likely to be a long way from each other so you need places to find each other closer to the action. This will help you and your friends to sample different cuisines, which is likely as your taste in food is probably not exactly the same. Be polite to the people sharing your table as they could become good friends. Drink lots of water and check the programme carefully so you don't miss any cooking demonstrations you want to see.\n§ 4. And when it's all over? Here's my number one request: before you go home, please pick up all your litter in and around your table. I can't believe the mess people create at festivals. Some people even leave their reusable plates behind. And as you leave, enjoy the feeling that you've just felt, with a wonderful connection to all those around you. You've just had an amazing weekend of sharing food and stories with total strangers, and that is something you don't forget.",
