        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "My summer with the elephants\nby Daniel Pritchard\n\n§ 1. At the age of 15 I have already decided that I want to be a wildlife biologist. So, last summer I persuaded my parents to let me spend our family holidays doing volunteer work abroad. I was especially keen on working with large mammals, so when a teacher told me about Tembo, the elephant conservation project in Kenya, I was thrilled because I would be leaving the UK for the first time and travelling to an incredible destination, but I had no idea how rewarding the trip would actually be or how many wonderful people I would meet along the way. Now, I would recommend this sort of volunteering to any student who wants to gain real work experience, or simply have fun and make friends from all over the world.\n\n§ 2. Elephants have roamed the African savannah for millions of years, but their numbers are falling fast because of illegal hunting and the loss of their natural habitat. This was a shock to me when I spent my first few days at a Rescue Centre in Nairobi before heading out to my main project. There, I learned that the majority of the young elephants at the centre had been orphaned when humans killed their mothers. Some of these killings happen for meat, but most are carried out by poachers who want the animals' tusks, which are sold at high prices on the black market. For local farmers, however, elephants can also be a nuisance, since hungry herds sometimes destroy crops in a single night, so some farmers view the elephants as their enemy, even though these animals are legally protected. And as if this were not enough for these gentle creatures to deal with, they also face the problem of a changing climate, which is drying up the water holes they depend on.\n\n§ 3. The following weeks were spent learning and having fun in four different camps, but the most memorable was the last one, where we stayed in a simple wooden lodge with no electricity and only a small tank of rainwater. However, the main difficulty was the mosquitoes, which shared the lodge with us, especially the ones that bit at night. But even that could not stop me from enjoying the daily walks with the young elephants, and relaxing around the campfire sharing stories after a long day of tracking and feeding. I had never slept under so many stars before.\n\n§ 4. I came home exhausted but with a wide smile on my face. I had dirt under my fingernails, a sunburned nose and a heart full of new memories. My parents could hardly recognise the confident young person who stepped off the plane. Looking back, the hot days, the insects and the cold showers were a small price to pay for the friendships I made and the animals I helped. I have already started saving up so that I can return next summer.",
