        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "Teacher Laura Bennett talks about setting up a school gardening club.\n\n§ 1. Last year the headteacher came into the staff room and asked me to start a gardening club. Our school already has plenty of excellent music and art clubs, which is wonderful, but not every pupil likes music or drawing. My classroom is decorated with pot plants I've grown, but they're not exactly prize-winning specimens and I wasn't sure I knew enough about horticulture to teach others. But I had wanted to run a school club for ages, and the headteacher promised a small budget for seeds, tools, compost, and so on — so I accepted.\n\n§ 2. There were so many things to think about before the first session, and I knew my colleagues were up to their eyes in marking and couldn't help. Should the club be for gardeners with experience? Should it be for the whole school, or only for sixth-formers? Above all, what did I actually want to achieve? To enter regional horticulture competitions, or just to grow vegetables for the school canteen? In the end I decided that my aim was simply for the students to enjoy growing things. I held the sessions in a disused greenhouse at the back of the school where we could lock our tools safely in a wooden chest.\n\n§ 3. Around twenty pupils came to the opening session. Some of them, I have to admit, had clearly only turned up to be with their friends. Still, I asked them all to sketch a simple plan for a flower bed. We put these up on the noticeboard and the more serious students talked about what might work well and what probably wouldn't. I hadn't expected them to have so many sensible ideas about colour, height and spacing.\n\n§ 4. The following week, almost all of the original students came back, and another thirty signed up. I had to ask the headteacher whether another teacher could share the sessions with me. Colleagues heard pupils chatting excitedly about the club in the corridors and started dropping by with suggestions for trips, including a visit to Kew Gardens. A full year on, I have no regrets about starting this club at all. The pupils have worked very hard on their plots. Some clearly have a natural flair for gardening, which definitely helps. I have already started planning next year's projects.",
