        "block": "reading",
        "blockLabel": "Reading Comprehension",
        "text": "The cost of a perfect break?\n\n§ 1. All-inclusive resorts are growing more and more popular, with around 35 million holidaymakers per year now enjoying breaks at large beachfront complexes. Many people see an all-inclusive as the perfect way to relax and switch off completely, and enjoy time away from the office. Everything you could possibly need is within easy reach. On site, there are bars, theatres, entertainment stages, swimming pools and gyms. There are actually more facilities than most villages offer their own residents. It's therefore easy to see why they are so popular. But what is the effect on the local environment of this trend?\n\n§ 2. Although it usually takes less energy to provide meals and drinks from a single kitchen than from dozens of small independent restaurants, all-inclusive resorts are often enormous, with the largest ones accommodating up to 5,000 guests at a time. Running such huge complexes requires vast generators, which burn as much as 250,000 litres of fuel a day. One environmental researcher has calculated that a single mega-resort creates as much air pollution as 4 million cars travelling over the same period. Because they are on remote coastlines, they also use generators that burn dirtier fuel than is allowed near inland cities. Unfortunately, few governments strictly monitor emissions on such isolated shores.\n\n§ 3. Resorts also produce huge amounts of rubbish, and all-inclusives aren't usually good at recycling. Waste water from showers and kitchens is frequently released almost directly into the sea — as much per day as from a small town. Uneaten food from the all-you-can-eat buffets isn't put into the sea, but still causes real problems when lorried back to the nearest landfill.\n\n§ 4. All-inclusive resorts also create difficulties in the nearby towns where guests occasionally venture. Popular destinations can see five or six coach-loads a day, with thousands of visitors at a time. Good for local restaurants? No. Family-run restaurant owners complain that the visitors look around for a couple of hours and then rush back to their resort to eat their pre-paid meals. What's more, the crowds can put off other tourists, who complain that the streets are suddenly too busy. Some towns have banned coach parties or put a limit on the number of resorts that can be built along a stretch of coast. People who care about the environment worry that as the all-inclusive industry continues to grow, so too will the problems for our planet.",
