        "text": "Martin Brooks writes about the digital camera\n\n§ 1. Looking back to my teenage years in the 1980s, I can remember dreaming of two gadgets I believed would transform my world but were probably not likely to exist in my lifetime. One was a device that could store thousands of photographs without any film, so I could take as many pictures as I wanted. The other was a tiny screen on the back that let me see a photo immediately after taking it. I often read about them in magazines, and they seemed impossibly futuristic to me!\n\n§ 2. I find it astonishing that during my adult life these two dreams have become ordinary. And not even two separate devices. Just one compact camera — or a camera built into the phone in my pocket, so small I barely notice its weight. I can capture thousands of images, share them with family and friends at once, edit photos on the move, or watch short films I have made myself. Thanks to automatic settings, I no longer have to worry about light or focus when I travel somewhere I have never been before. I can learn photography techniques online, join communities of photographers around the world, and print my pictures at home… the list goes on.\n\n§ 3. Together with the Internet, the digital camera must be one of the biggest changes in everyday technology. So why do many of us feel uneasy about how often we raise a camera in front of our eyes? It's strange that the tool which captures memories seems to have reduced the time we actually spend enjoying what is happening around us. We are all used to seeing tourists and families who are always framing a scene through a screen and barely noticing the real world in front of them.\n\n§ 4. The digital camera is here to stay and we must find a way of dealing with the habits it encourages. I believe these are habits we have to change individually rather than expecting someone else to solve the problem for us. It's up to us to be careful about when we reach for the camera and remember that it's good to watch a moment without recording it. We can still be amazed that we own such a powerful tool, while choosing to put it down from time to time.",
