        "text": "Husky sledding in Finland\nby Louis Petersen, aged 15\n\n§ 1. Last winter, Dad and I wanted to try a winter sport called husky sledding — travelling across the snow on a sled pulled by a team of dogs. And pictures of one area in Finnish Lapland, with teams of dogs racing through silent pine forests, persuaded us that destination was a good choice. We hadn't done any dog-sports before, though, so we weren't sure how difficult husky sledding would be, compared with other winter activities. But we signed up to join a small group of people, of all ages, plus an experienced musher.\n\n§ 2. We'd read about the place we went to before we left, so we knew it was close to where Finland ends and Russia starts. And our family knew we wouldn't be able to message home often, as the mobile signal was very weak — and actually, it was relaxing to be far from anywhere, or anyone. What we hadn't realised was that from there, at certain times of year, we'd be able to watch the magical green curtains of the Northern Lights dancing above the trees — what a sight!\n\n§ 3. On our first day there, I hated getting up in the dark, but it meant I saw the sun rise pink over the snowy forest, so I was glad I did. And clear weather was forecast for the week, I was delighted to hear! But the real problem was my 15kg rucksack, full of warm clothes and emergency food — I had no idea it would weigh so much. Anyway, we travelled for hours across mainly flat tracks. Having light sleds was supposed to help us climb the few small hills along the way — although the dogs still struggled on the steeper parts!\n\n§ 4. Finally we stopped for the night. It wasn't until we'd reached our log cabin that our musher mentioned we'd just crossed a frozen river to get there — but nothing surprised us by that point! Anyway, he gave us all jobs to do — chopping firewood, feeding the dogs and preparing dinner — and soon we were eating a hot meal, made from whatever food we'd brought — a strange mix, but it tasted delicious. And the snowy night was so peaceful outside that none of us stayed awake long. Dad and I want to try another winter adventure next year, maybe ice climbing. But we'll probably end up just as exhausted as we were after this trip!",
